). Body small (
<quantity box="[620,726,1869,1893]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.39" pageId="1" unit="mm" value="9.39">9.39 mm</quantity>
long) (
<figureCitation box="[815,945,1868,1893]" captionStart="FIGURE 1 A – H" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1930,1952]" captionTargetBox="[175,1429,567,1857]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[162,1447,525,1896]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1 A – H. Hedotettix angulatus sp. nov. Female A, Body in dorsal view; B, Body in lateral view; C, Head in frontal view. D, Antenna; E, Fore legs in external view; F, Hind femur in external view; G, Mid leg in external view; H, Pulvilli and hind tarsus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/159880/files/figure.png" pageId="1">Fig. 1A, B</figureCitation>
), smooth, vertex distinctly broader than a compound eye in dorsal view and strongly concave in frontal view. Median carina of the vertex angulate, strong, situated in the distal end of the length of the vertex (
<figureCitation box="[740,825,1940,1965]" captionStart="FIGURE 3 A – I. A" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1836,1858]" captionTargetBox="[156,1429,204,1798]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,195,1811]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3 A – I. A, Hedotettix angulatus sp. nov., showing tegmen; B, Hedotettix grossus tegmen; C, Hedotettix angulatus sp. nov., head in dorsal view, showing median carina of vertex; D, Hedotettix angulatus sp. nov. posterior margin of the lateral lobe of pronotum; E, Hedotettix grossus head showing median carina of vertex; F, Ovipositor valves; G, Hedotettix grossus head in frontal view; H, Hedotettix grossus; I, pronotum apex and hind wings apex." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/159882/files/figure.png" pageId="1">Fig. 3C</figureCitation>
) and elevated. Fossullae present, lateral carinae of the vertex present, strongly elevated with small tubercles. Supraocular lobes present. Vertex slightly wider than compound eye. Median ocellus situated far below the level of the lower margin of the compound eyes, in the place where facial carinae end. Lateral ocelli situated slightly above the level of the middle height of the compound eyes. Frontal costa bifurcates into facial carinae above the paired ocelli and facial carinae run parallel to the median ocellus, forming scutellum. Antennal grooves are situated above the lower margin of the compound eyes. Antennal grooves wider than scutellum, scapus wider than scutellum (
<figureCitation box="[859,951,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 1 A – H" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1930,1952]" captionTargetBox="[175,1429,567,1857]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[162,1447,525,1896]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1 A – H. Hedotettix angulatus sp. nov. Female A, Body in dorsal view; B, Body in lateral view; C, Head in frontal view. D, Antenna; E, Fore legs in external view; F, Hind femur in external view; G, Mid leg in external view; H, Pulvilli and hind tarsus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/159880/files/figure.png" pageId="2">Fig. 1C</figureCitation>
). Eyes in frontal view slightly elongated, ovoid; in lateral view sub-globular with rounded margin proximal to pronotum; in dorsal view sub-globular. Eyes can be positioned slightly distant from the pronotum, so the occipital area is present, visible. Antennae 14–15 segmented (
<figureCitation box="[286,375,370,395]" captionStart="FIGURE 1 A – H" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1930,1952]" captionTargetBox="[175,1429,567,1857]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[162,1447,525,1896]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1 A – H. Hedotettix angulatus sp. nov. Female A, Body in dorsal view; B, Body in lateral view; C, Head in frontal view. D, Antenna; E, Fore legs in external view; F, Hind femur in external view; G, Mid leg in external view; H, Pulvilli and hind tarsus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/159880/files/figure.png" pageId="2">Fig. 1D</figureCitation>
). Antennal article 1 is scapus, 3–6 are not long at all or 7th to 13th are long. Mid segment about 3 times as long as wide. Segments 14th–15th (14th) are reduced and filiform. Pre-subapical antennal segments (2–8) are dark brown, subapical and apical dark.
</paragraph>
