<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1453,2018]" pageId="5">
Pronotum granulated, with fine and small tubercles, wrinkled, projected far beyond the hind knees (for one third length of the hind tibiae), slender, anterior margin truncated. Median carina is continuous towards the whole length of pronotum, anterior region depressed, compressed, elevated. Prozonal carinae strong, visible, elevated, in the end of prozona curved in the direction of median carina. Extra lateral carinae strong, elevated, normal. The length of prozona of pronotum variable. Extra lateral carinae fused to humero-apical carinae and forming slightly convex, with obtuse rounded angle. Interhumeral carinae indistinct. Interscapular area narrower (2.1) than mid femur width, without fused to lateral area and runs towards the apex of the pronotum. Lateral area wider than interscapular area. Pronotum apex truncated, slightly crenulated (
<figureCitation box="[926,997,1705,1730]" captionStart="FIGURE 3 A – I. A" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1836,1858]" captionTargetBox="[156,1429,204,1798]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,195,1811]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3 A – I. A, Hedotettix angulatus sp. nov., showing tegmen; B, Hedotettix grossus tegmen; C, Hedotettix angulatus sp. nov., head in dorsal view, showing median carina of vertex; D, Hedotettix angulatus sp. nov. posterior margin of the lateral lobe of pronotum; E, Hedotettix grossus head showing median carina of vertex; F, Ovipositor valves; G, Hedotettix grossus head in frontal view; H, Hedotettix grossus; I, pronotum apex and hind wings apex." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/159882/files/figure.png" pageId="5">
Fig. 
<date box="[974,997,1705,1730]" pageId="5">3I</date>
</figureCitation>
). Two lateral pronotal lobes present, posterior margin of the lateral lobe slightly narrower. The tegminal and ventral sinus present.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1453,2018]" pageId="5">
Tegmina rhomboid in shape and with concave ventral margin (
<figureCitation box="[918,1001,1777,1802]" captionStart="FIGURE 3 A – I. A" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1836,1858]" captionTargetBox="[156,1429,204,1798]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,195,1811]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3 A – I. A, Hedotettix angulatus sp. nov., showing tegmen; B, Hedotettix grossus tegmen; C, Hedotettix angulatus sp. nov., head in dorsal view, showing median carina of vertex; D, Hedotettix angulatus sp. nov. posterior margin of the lateral lobe of pronotum; E, Hedotettix grossus head showing median carina of vertex; F, Ovipositor valves; G, Hedotettix grossus head in frontal view; H, Hedotettix grossus; I, pronotum apex and hind wings apex." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/159882/files/figure.png" pageId="5">Fig.3A</figureCitation>
). Alae present, reaching or surpassing the hind process of the pronotum (about 
<quantity box="[606,710,1813,1838]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.15" pageId="5" unit="mm" value="2.15">2.15 mm</quantity>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1453,2018]" lastBlockId="6.[151,1437,151,939]" lastPageId="6" pageId="5">
All the femora finely serrated. Fore and mid femora laterally compressed (
<figureCitation box="[1049,1173,1849,1874]" captionStart="FIGURE 1 A – H" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1930,1952]" captionTargetBox="[175,1429,567,1857]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[162,1447,525,1896]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1 A – H. Hedotettix angulatus sp. nov. Female A, Body in dorsal view; B, Body in lateral view; C, Head in frontal view. D, Antenna; E, Fore legs in external view; F, Hind femur in external view; G, Mid leg in external view; H, Pulvilli and hind tarsus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/159880/files/figure.png" pageId="5">Fig. 1E, G</figureCitation>
). Length/width ratio of fore femora 3.8, of mid femora 4. Fore and mid tibiae slender. Upper and lower margins of fore and mid femur straight; width of midfemur narrower than the width of tegmina. Tarsi of fore and mid femora with proximal segment significantly shorter than the distal one. Hind femora 3 times as long as wide and serrated (
<figureCitation box="[1269,1352,1957,1982]" captionStart="FIGURE 1 A – H" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1930,1952]" captionTargetBox="[175,1429,567,1857]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[162,1447,525,1896]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1 A – H. Hedotettix angulatus sp. nov. Female A, Body in dorsal view; B, Body in lateral view; C, Head in frontal view. D, Antenna; E, Fore legs in external view; F, Hind femur in external view; G, Mid leg in external view; H, Pulvilli and hind tarsus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/159880/files/figure.png" pageId="5">Fig. 1F</figureCitation>
), tibiae with 11outer and 10 inner spines. Dorsal external area with a large tubercle. Genicular and antigenicular teeth visible, acute, small. Length of 1st tarsal segment 1.6 times longer than the third segment, tip of pulvilli Ist spinulately produced, IInd pulvilli without spinulately and IIIrd slightly spinulately produced, apices of all the pulvilli obtuse, pulvilli III distinctly shorter than length of I, II pulvilli together (
<figureCitation box="[1128,1222,226,251]" captionStart="FIGURE 1 A – H" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1930,1952]" captionTargetBox="[175,1429,567,1857]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[162,1447,525,1896]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1 A – H. Hedotettix angulatus sp. nov. Female A, Body in dorsal view; B, Body in lateral view; C, Head in frontal view. D, Antenna; E, Fore legs in external view; F, Hind femur in external view; G, Mid leg in external view; H, Pulvilli and hind tarsus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/159880/files/figure.png" pageId="6">Fig. 1H</figureCitation>
). Subgenital plate rectangular in ventral view, its length slightly longer than its width. Ovipositor robust, length of upper valves 2.2 times its width (
<figureCitation box="[331,410,298,323]" captionStart="FIGURE 3 A – I. A" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1836,1858]" captionTargetBox="[156,1429,204,1798]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,195,1811]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3 A – I. A, Hedotettix angulatus sp. nov., showing tegmen; B, Hedotettix grossus tegmen; C, Hedotettix angulatus sp. nov., head in dorsal view, showing median carina of vertex; D, Hedotettix angulatus sp. nov. posterior margin of the lateral lobe of pronotum; E, Hedotettix grossus head showing median carina of vertex; F, Ovipositor valves; G, Hedotettix grossus head in frontal view; H, Hedotettix grossus; I, pronotum apex and hind wings apex." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/159882/files/figure.png" pageId="6">Fig.3F</figureCitation>
). Cerci small, slender with rounded apex, with long hairs.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,939]" pageId="6">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,269,334,359]" pageId="6">Male:</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[285,406,334,359]" captionStart="FIGURE 2 A – C" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1773,1795]" captionTargetBox="[160,1415,222,1740]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,195,1749]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2 A – C. Hedotettix angulatus sp. nov. Male A, Body in dorsal view; B, Subgenital platein lateral view; C, Body in lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/159881/files/figure.png" pageId="6">Fig. 2A–C</figureCitation>
) Body size smaller than female, feature of structure similar to female. Subgenital plate 2.6 times as long as wide, apex with V-shaped incision (
<figureCitation box="[737,825,370,395]" captionStart="FIGURE 2 A – C" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1773,1795]" captionTargetBox="[160,1415,222,1740]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,195,1749]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2 A – C. Hedotettix angulatus sp. nov. Male A, Body in dorsal view; B, Subgenital platein lateral view; C, Body in lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/159881/files/figure.png" pageId="6">Fig. 2B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,939]" pageId="6">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,406,431]" pageId="6">Coloration.</emphasis>
Body brown to blackish-brown. Body color varies from brown to blackish. Antenna brown, apical part dark-brown. Pronotal tubercles usually dark brown. Distal part of all the tibiae and tarsi usually black- reddish or dark black, with white long hairs, tip of spine black.
</paragraph>
